In different domain environments, there are different DNS servers, meaning that addressing needs to cross routes. Nettcpbinding only works in the same intranet environment. For service scenarios on the Internet, I recommend using wshttpbinding.  
[https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/wcf/feature-details/configuring-system-provided-bindings][1]  
If it is a friend domain, on the basis of ensuring the network is smooth and trusting each other, we can use the message security mode (Nettcpbiniding default security mode) and use windows credentials to ensure message security.
As for authentication with a certificate, the hyperlink is too old, please attempt the Powershell to create the self-signed certificate.  
&gt; New-SelfSignedCertificate -DnsName &quot;Currenthostname&quot;
&gt; -CertStoreLocation &quot;cert:\LocalMachine\My&quot;  

Link.  
[https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/pkiclient/new-selfsignedcertificate?view=win10-ps][2]  
The certificate should be configured on the server-side. Please refer to the below code snippet.

     &lt;system.serviceModel&gt;
        &lt;services&gt;
          &lt;service name=&quot;ConsoleApp3.TestService&quot; behaviorConfiguration=&quot;mybehavior&quot;&gt;
            &lt;endpoint address=&quot;&quot; binding=&quot;netTcpBinding&quot; contract=&quot;ConsoleApp3.ITestService&quot; bindingConfiguration=&quot;mybinding&quot; &gt;&lt;/endpoint&gt;
            &lt;endpoint address=&quot;mex&quot; binding=&quot;mexTcpBinding&quot; contract=&quot;IMetadataExchange&quot;&gt;&lt;/endpoint&gt;
            &lt;host&gt;
              &lt;baseAddresses&gt;
